{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"2fcb66df-8855-4d6f-9609-2f318fe05fa8","content":"In .NET MAUI, those `Application`-level overrides are gone. Instead, use **`Window` lifecycle events**. Override `CreateWindow` in your `Application` class:\n\n```csharp\nprotected override Window CreateWindow(IActivationState? activationState)\n{\n    var window = base.CreateWindow(activationState);\n\n    window.Created += (s, e) => { /* OnStart equivalent */ };\n    window.Stopped += (s, e) => { /* OnSleep equivalent */ };\n    window.Resumed += (s, e) => { /* OnResume equivalent */ };\n    window.Destroying += (s, e) => { /* cleanup */ };\n\n    return window;\n}\n```\n\nAlternatively, subclass `Window` and override `OnCreated`, `OnStopped`, `OnResumed`, etc.\n\nFor **platform-specific** lifecycle hooks, use `ConfigureLifecycleEvents` in `MauiProgram.cs`:\n\n```csharp\nbuilder.ConfigureLifecycleEvents(events =>\n{\n#if ANDROID\n    events.AddAndroid(android => android.OnStop(activity => { /* ... */ }));\n#elif IOS\n    events.AddiOS(ios => ios.OnActivated(app => { /* ... */ }));\n#endif\n});\n```","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"3d3f7575-986c-481b-89db-3e3c08a9b728","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about migrating lifecycle methods from Xamarin.Forms to .NET MAUI. This is a knowledge question I can answer directly without needing to search the codebase.\n\nIn Xamarin.Forms, you'd override `OnStart()`, `OnSleep()`, and `OnResume()` in your `Application` subclass.\n\nIn .NET MAUI, the equivalent is to use the `Window` lifecycle events or the cross-platform lifecycle events via `ConfigureLifecycleEvents` in `MauiProgram.cs`, or override the `CreateWindow` method and hook into `Window` events.\n\n\nThe lifecycle method mappings are roughly `OnStart` to `Window.Created`, `OnSleep` to `Window.Deactivated` or `Window.Stopped`, and `OnResume` to `Window.Resumed` or `Window.Activated`. Actually, I need to clarify—the `Application` class in .NET MAUI doesn't have those same lifecycle methods that existed in Xamarin.Forms, so you'll need to rely on the `Window` events instead.\n\nIn .NET MAUI, you work with the `Window` class which exposes events like `Created`, `Stopped`, `Resumed`, and `Destroying`, or you can override the corresponding virtual methods like `OnCreated`, `OnStopped`, `OnResumed`, and `OnDestroying` in a custom `Window` subclass. You typically hook into these by overriding `CreateWindow` in your `Application` class or by configuring the lifecycle through `ILifecycleBuilder` in `MauiProgram.cs`.","outputTokens":802,"requestId":"DC07:127F79:ACBA4:DA690:69F54B6C"},"id":"a0176443-87cc-49a3-b0b0-4ab2319c76ef","timestamp":"2026-05-02T00:55:23.500Z","parentId":"d829b1a0-0482-4315-baa1-c5cb812cfc4c"}
